stanford university department of statistics departmental seminar page 1 stanford university department of statistics departmental seminar 4 15 pm tuesday may 26 2009 sequoia hall room 200 cookies at 3 45 in 1st floor lounge jonathan levin department of economics stanford university an analysis of subprime lending between 1995 and 2007 there was a dramatic expansion in credit extended to households with poor credit records and high risk of subsequent default we use data from a large subprime lender to explore what changes in the types of loans being offered might have triggered the huge increase in borrowing and what might have prompted lenders to make these loans the evidence points to a central role played by changes in loan to value ratios as opposed to interest rates which are typically the key variable emphasized by policy makers we also explore how the adoption of sophisticated credit scoring methods affected the workings of consumer loan markets
